		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2008"></a><br><code>sle2008/paper18</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2008</a> paper:</span><br><i>The Java Programmer’s Phrase Book</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/EinarWHøst.html">Einar W. Høst</a>, <a href="../profile/BjarteMØstvold.html">Bjarte M. Østvold</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-00434-6_20">10.1007/978-3-642-00434-6_20</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5e.html"><span class="tagM">T5E: Empirical Evaluation</span></a><ul><li> It builds an automatically generated phrase book from a large corpus of Java programs, relying on empirical analysis of real-world usage.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagL">T5B: Language Description Analysis</span></a><ul><li> It analyzes the structure and ‘semantics’ of method-name phrases, treating identifier naming as a describable language.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2b.html"><span class="tagL">T2B: Evolution</span></a><ul><li> The motivation includes supporting developers as code and naming conventions evolve (e.g., guiding/refactoring names).
</li></ul></li></ul>
